{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1c43c188-0ec0-426f-b866-3d0ed16728cd","content":"**Use `dotnet workload update`.**\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the latest versions of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is what brings your MAUI workload back in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-installs workloads that are already recorded but may have corrupted or missing files. It does **not** upgrade versions.\n\nSince your issue is a version mismatch from the SDK update, run:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf the build still fails after that, try `dotnet workload repair` as a follow-up in case any files are in a bad state.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"83bbf5a3-a7fb-444b-8dc2-23e6d53091a7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI workload management — specifically whether to use `dotnet workload update` or `dotnet workload repair` after a SDK update broke their build. This is a general knowledge question, not a codebase task.","outputTokens":234,"requestId":"981C:155537:165B099:18E123F:6A051DA4"},"id":"b25febdd-d76a-4bb2-b594-b167920d6645","timestamp":"2026-05-14T00:56:12.388Z","parentId":"df2fe2a6-2e8c-481e-9085-6f259c2b10b7"}
